def replace_mileage_units(mil_units):
    """
    This function look for km/kg and kmpl in the Mileage and replace them with empty space ("")
    """
    if isinstance(mil_units, str):  # checks if 'rmil_units' is a string
        if mil_units.endswith("km/kg"):
            return float(mil_units.replace("km/kg", ""))
        elif mil_units.endswith("kmpl"):
            return (
                float(mil_units.replace("kmpl", ""))
            )  
    else: 
        return np.nan

Summary of EDA¶

Observations from EDA:¶

The price is heavily right-skewed, The mean is around 5.6 lakhs¶

The power, Mileage , engine all have positive influence on the price.¶

where as KM_Driven, Year have negative influence on the price.¶

Mumbai location has more inventory. The price is also not that high compared to other¶

Automated transmission cars can sell at higher price compared to manual ones.¶

Most of the cars are Diesel and Petrol.¶

Wide variety of cars are available it is not good to set one price. One size does not fit all.¶

First hand cars have higher prices compared other ones followed by 2nd hand cars. third and fourth ones have out lier¶

The Target variable (price)is of float type.¶

Name is object type.¶

Location, Fuel_Type, Transmission, Owner_Type are category types¶

Rest of the fields are float types¶

There are no duplicate records in the data¶

There are missing values in the data. The rows with missing data have been dropped.¶

def r_squared(model, X, y):
    y_mean = y.mean()
    SST = ((y - y_mean) ** 2).sum()
    SSE = ((y - model.predict(X)) ** 2).sum()
    r_square = 1 - SSE / SST
    return SSE, SST, r_square


SSE, SST, r_square = r_squared(lin_reg_model, x_train, y_train)

In [91]:
#create a function that will print out all the above metrics in one go.

# function to compute adjusted R-squared
def adj_r2_score(predictors, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = predictors.shape[0]
    k = predictors.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))


# function to compute MAPE
def mape_score(targets, predictions):
    return np.mean(np.abs(targets - predictions) / targets) * 100


# function to compute different metrics to check performance of a regression model
def model_performance_regression(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check regression model performance

    model: regressor
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    r2 = r2_score(target, pred)  # to compute R-squared
    adjr2 = adj_r2_score(predictors, target, pred)  # to compute adjusted R-squared
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(target, pred))  # to compute RMSE
    mae = mean_absolute_error(target, pred)  # to compute MAE
    mape = mape_score(target, pred)  # to compute MAPE

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "RMSE": rmse,
            "MAE": mae,
            "R-squared": r2,
            "Adj. R-squared": adjr2,
            "MAPE": mape,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

Conclusions¶

Like I mentioned in the beginning¶

it is hard to a set up right price for all the makes and models.¶

It is very hard to recommend unique price across all makes, models and locations.¶

Each city location dealer should come up with their own price model based on the above statistics.¶

But in general they can start pricing their cars above .44 lakhs regardless of the location, year, make etc..¶

This is not recommended price , but just a statistical view to give confidence.¶

Probably non-linear transformation may improve the performance of the above regression model¶
